<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>white as a sheet • white as snow</xh5><p> <i>white as a sheet—</i>very pale, usually because of illness, shock or fear: He must have done a pretty good imitation of a gangster because the guy’s face turned <u>white as a sheet</u>.</p><p> <i>white as snow—</i>is said of very pure white color: Anne walked with him to the house up the brook, over a field that was as <u>white as snow</u> with daisies.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> Neither expression correlates in meaning with the phrase <b>whiter than white</b>—<i>said of a good and righteous man: </i>Having come to power promising to be “<u>whiter than white</u>,” Blair’s government may find it difficult to redeem its once spotless reputation.</p> </entry>
